    {
      "id": "5a93c517_fdf2ba04",
      "file_path": "openecomp-be/lib/openecomp-core-lib/openecomp-utilities-lib/src/main/java/org/openecomp/core/utilities/file/FileUtils.java",
      "patchset_number": 4,
      "line": 303,
      "message": "Well, calling a method is always more expensive than using a variable. Here it's multiplied by the number of iterations. Premature optimization is evil, but this doesn't mean you don't have to care about performance at all. Very likely it will be eventually optimized by the JVM, but why not do it right away? You can use JMH to benchmark the difference.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 329,
        "name": "Vitaly Emporopulo",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "Vitaliy.Emporopulo@amdocs.com",
        "username": "vempo"
      },
      "updated": "2018-03-06 11:13:36.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "5a93c517_62512735",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "5a93c517_1dae8698",
      "file_path": "openecomp-be/lib/openecomp-core-lib/openecomp-utilities-lib/src/main/java/org/openecomp/core/utilities/file/FileUtils.java",
      "patchset_number": 4,
      "line": 328,
      "message": "Yes, the general rule is simple: Don't write what's been already written. Reasons? Time to write, time to test, probable bugs, copyright violations if pasted from somewhere. There was even a session on doing code reviews that explicitly mentioned it. Most of the popular frameworks for common tasks are already included as Maven dependencies anyway.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 329,
        "name": "Vitaly Emporopulo",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "Vitaliy.Emporopulo@amdocs.com",
        "username": "vempo"
      },
      "updated": "2018-03-06 11:13:36.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "5a93c517_0244e371",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "5a93c517_9d705641",
      "file_path": "openecomp-be/lib/openecomp-tosca-lib/src/main/java/org/openecomp/sdc/tosca/services/impl/ToscaValidationServiceImpl.java",
      "patchset_number": 4,
      "line": 68,
      "message": "It doesn't explain. Look at the code - it either always, unconditionally overwrites the \"issues\" variable, or throws an exception, in which case it can't return anything. And suppose you needed to return an instance - return a sized HashMap or better yet Collections.emptyMap() (immutability is a bonus).",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 329,
        "name": "Vitaly Emporopulo",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "Vitaliy.Emporopulo@amdocs.com",
        "username": "vempo"
      },
      "updated": "2018-03-06 11:13:36.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "5a93c517_424e6b98",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "5a93c517_dd933e59",
      "file_path": "openecomp-be/lib/openecomp-tosca-lib/src/main/java/org/openecomp/sdc/tosca/services/impl/ToscaValidationServiceImpl.java",
      "patchset_number": 4,
      "line": 83,
      "message": "Yes, it looks like a one-time initialization. Concurrently doesn't mean multi-threaded in this case. Just some other code would like to put there other values. Also, I can understand why the configuration manager is intitialized/modified outside. In other words the set() APIs are problematic.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 329,
        "name": "Vitaly Emporopulo",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "Vitaliy.Emporopulo@amdocs.com",
        "username": "vempo"
      },
      "updated": "2018-03-06 11:13:36.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "5a93c517_fd571ac8",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "5a93c517_9d99367b",
      "file_path": "openecomp-be/lib/openecomp-tosca-lib/src/main/java/org/openecomp/sdc/tosca/services/impl/ToscaValidationServiceImpl.java",
      "patchset_number": 4,
      "line": 113,
      "message": "On the face of it, the stream is traversed once to filter by the first predicate, and then once more to filter the result by the second predicate. I believe you wouldn't have written two loops with an intermediate result. There are other ways to achieve readability - extract the complex condition to a method, for instance.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 329,
        "name": "Vitaly Emporopulo",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "Vitaliy.Emporopulo@amdocs.com",
        "username": "vempo"
      },
      "updated": "2018-03-06 11:13:36.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "5a93c517_e2ae972d",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "5a93c517_dd7a5e23",
      "file_path": "openecomp-be/lib/openecomp-tosca-lib/src/main/java/org/openecomp/sdc/tosca/services/impl/ToscaValidationServiceImpl.java",
      "patchset_number": 4,
      "line": 120,
      "message": "This is what I mean https://stackoverflow.com/a/18600383/3365419. I'm not sure how Yaml.load() is implemented, and I don't care much because the only thing I know from the API is that it accepts an InputStream that can be attached to any source. On the other hand, I know that in our case it's a file, and its FileInputStream's low level operations are expensive.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 329,
        "name": "Vitaly Emporopulo",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "Vitaliy.Emporopulo@amdocs.com",
        "username": "vempo"
      },
      "updated": "2018-03-06 11:13:36.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "5a93c517_bd751265",
      "unresolved": false
    },
